======================================================================================================================





CONTENTS OF THIS DIRECTORY
--------------------------

	1) SUB-DIRECTORIES
	------------------

		- cluster/	Contains the abundance measurements (and measured X/Fe ratios) of all the CHEERS 
				sample. Results are reported within 0.05r_500, as well as within 0.2r_500 (when 
				possible). The average abundance pattern is also available, under the original results 
				measured using SPEX 2.05 (average_CHEERS.out) and its corresponding SPEX 3.03 
				correction (average_CHEERS_SPEX3.out). For more information, see 
				Mernier, F., de Plaa, J., Pinto, et al. 2016a, A&A, 592, A157 
				and 
				Mernier, F., de Plaa, Kaastra, J. S, et al. (submitted).

		- raw_tables_literature/	Contains some supernova yield tables retrieved directly from the 
						literature. These raw tables are not used directly in abunfit.py.

		- AGB/		Contains the predicted yields from AGB contributions (Nomoto et al. 2013; adapted from 
				Karakas 2010). Note that the AGB contribution used in abunfit.py has not been tested 
				extensively. You will use it at your own risk!

		- SNcc/		Contains the predicted yields from SNcc contributions (Heger & Woosley 2002, 2010, Chieffi 
				& Limongi 2004, Nomoto et al. 2006, 2013). Compared to Nomoto et al. (2006), the Nomoto
				et al. (2013) yields contain an addditional model of initial metallicity of Z=0.008, 
				as well as slightly updated calculations (e.g. taking into account the full decay of some 
				unstable isotopes). The models of Nomoto et al. (2006) have also been corrected from the 
				full decay of unstable isotopes. The original values from Nomoto et al. (2006) are marked 
				by the "_undecayed" suffix. In abunfit.py, all these SNcc yields are IMF-integrated (with 
				an IMF slope selected by the user) from 10 M_sun to 40 M_sun, if the initial metallicity Z>0. 
				For the Z=0 models, the integration covers up to 140 M_sun. The Z=0 yields from Heger & 
				Woosley (2002,2010) and Nomoto et al. (2013) are also predicted for pair-instability supernovae 
				(PISNe, typically for >140 M_sun). A complete integration over the full mass range 
				(SNcc+PISNe) is also proposed ("_SNe" suffix). The yields from Nomoto et al. (2013) are 
				also predicted for hypernovae (HNe).

		- SNIa/		Contains the predicted yields from SNIa contributions (Iwamoto et al. 1999, Badenes et al. 
				2006, Maeda et al. 2010, Pakmor et al. 2010, Waldman et al. 2011, Seitenzahl et al. 2013, 
				Fink et al. 2014). The (1D) Iwamoto et al. (1999, incl. deflagration and delayed-detonation) 
				yields are the most widely used in the literature, although somewhat outdated. The (1D) 
				Badenes et al. (2006) yields are based on delayed-detonation models that fit well the spectral 
				features of the Tycho supernova. The Maeda et al. (2010) yields contain 2D deflagration and 
				delayed detonation models, as well as an updated version of the 1D Iwamoto et al. (1999) W7 
				yields (including more realistic calculations of the electron capture rates). The Seitenzahl 
				et al. (2013, delayed-detonation) and Fink et al. (2014, deflagration) yields are the most 
				recent ones, and are modelled for 3D explosions. The Waldman et al. (2011) yields are to be 
				used in the case of Ca-rich gap transients. The Pakmor et al. (2010) yields (and its orginal 
				"undecayed" version, i.e. without fully accounting the decay of unstable isotopes) are 
				predictions from the sub_Chandrasekhar channel, assuming a violent merger between two white 
				dwarfs (as part of the double-degenerate scenario).


	2) FILES
	--------

		- abunfit.py	Main routine described above. To make it run, you need python, as well as the libraries os, 
				sys, math, numpy, and scipy. 

				The input files are:
				- A list of the measured X/Fe abundance ratios (found in cluster/, or of similar format). 
				  Note that the script is not (yet) suitable for absolute (X) abundance measurements. 
				- One, two, three, or four input yield models, as those described above (to be selected from 
				  models.txt). The format of these file depend on the type of model (SNIa or SNcc).
				- A reference (solar or proto-solar) abundance table. Here we use lodders09.txt, i.e. the 
				  proto-solar values of Lodders et al. (2009).
				- A table containing the atomic mass of each element (atomic_masses.txt).

				The output files are:
				- output.dat: A table showing the element number (1st column), input abundance ratios (X/Fe) 
				  and their respective error bars (2nd and 3rd columns), and the respective contribution of 
				  each yield model (4th,... columns).
				- output.qdp: Similar as output.dat, optimized to be read by QDP 
				  (https://heasarc.gsfc.nasa.gov/lheasoft/ftools/others/qdp/qdp.html) and displayed in a graph.
				/!\ Each new run of abunfit.py will overwrite the pre-exisiting output files!

		- serial_fitter.sh	Bash script running a series of abundance fits (abunfit.py) with various yield models 
					and/or IMF slopes. All the tested combinations are then folded by increasing chi^2 (via 
					the routine sort_summary_models.py) into summary_models.txt. The best-fit compination of 
					models is stored in best_model.txt.



